<DOC><DOCNO> AP890827-0062 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-27-89 2304EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r a AM-BRF--O'HareAccident     08-27 0176</FIRST><SECOND>AM-BRF--O'Hare Accident,0181</SECOND><HEAD>Mechanic Loses Leg Crushed by Taxiing Jet</HEAD><DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A 22-year-old airline mechanic lost her lowerright leg after she was run over by a taxiing jet at O'HareInternational Airport, her surgeon said Sunday.   Hope Lewellen, 22, of Orland Park was in critical but stablecondition at Lutheran General Hospital in suburban Park Ridge afternine hours of surgery to repair injuries to both legs sufferedSaturday, said Dr. Wayne Goldstein.   Ms. Lewellen, a Continental Airlines employee, had been directinga Scandinavian Airlines 767 jet to a gate for departure toStockholm, Sweden, when she was run over.   Ms. Lewellen leaned down to pick up earphones that had fallen offher head, and the pilot did not know she was still behind theaircraft, which was backing up, said Patrolman Dan Cirighini of thepolice department's O'Hare unit.   Continental employees were the only people aboard the plane atthe time, said airline spokeswoman Marj Abrams. Continental is undercontract with Scandinavian Airlines to service Scandinavian's jetsin the United States.</TEXT></DOC>